23.1 Definition: metric space
A metric space is a set \(S\) with a distance function
\[
d:S\times S\to \mathbb{R}
\]
such that for all \(x,y,z\in S\),

\(d(x,y)\ge 0\) and \(d(x,y)=0\) if and only if \(x=y\);
\(d(x,y)=d(y,x)\);
\(d(x,z)\le d(x,y)+d(y,z)\).

23.3 Definition: normed vector space and Banach space
A norm on a vector space \(V\) is a function
\[
\|\cdot\|:V\to\mathbb{R}
\]
such that for all \(u,v\in V\) and scalars \(c\),

\(\|v\|\ge 0\) and \(\|v\|=0\) if and only if \(v=0\);
\(\|cv\|=|c|\|v\|\);
\(\|u+v\|\le \|u\|+\|v\|\).

A complete normed vector space is called a Banach space.

23.1 Definition 1: Topological data analysis
Topological data analysis is a collection of methods that uses topological constructions and invariants to study data. A common workflow is:

start with data, often a point cloud \(X\subseteq \mathbb R^d\);
build a simplicial complex from the data;
convert the complex into boundary matrices;
compute homology using linear algebra;
track homology across scales using persistent homology.

A graph becomes a linear algebra object when we encode it as a matrix.
Its eigenvalues and eigenvectors then reveal connectivity, geometry, clustering, and dynamics.








